## **What Is a Radiant Cut Diamond? Origins, Design, and Definition**

### **What are radiant cut diamonds?**

First designed in the late 1970s, the radiant cut was a revolution. It was the first square-shaped cut to have a complete brilliant-cut facet pattern on both the crown and pavilion. It was created in 1977 by master cutter Henry Grossbard, who wanted to combine the brilliance of a round diamond with the clean, rectangular shape of an emerald cut.

The result was something bold and different — an angular shape that still managed to catch light from every direction.

The radiant cut features a rectangular or square outline with 45-degree clipped corners — creating an octagonal silhouette when viewed face-up. Unlike the emerald cut (which uses step-cut facets to produce the hall-of-mirrors effect), the radiant cut applies brilliant-cut triangular and kite-shaped facets across its entire crown and pavilion.

This is what makes it unique among rectangular shapes: emerald cuts have a glassier, more reserved look due to only having 57 facets, while radiant cuts are more vibrant with 70 facets — the extra facets creating more fire and brilliance.

I'm **Farzana Hasan**, a GIA Expert. The radiant cut is one of the most technically interesting shapes in the market — a genuine engineering achievement that solved the problem of rectangular diamonds losing brilliance. This guide covers everything: the 70-facet architecture, the complete live price data, the critical proportion specifications GIA does not grade, and every comparison question buyers ask. Full credentials at **[Diamond Critics](https://diamondcritics.com/about-farzana/)**.

