## **How Many Facets Does a Radiant Cut Diamond Have? The 70-Facet Architecture**

**The radiant cut has 70 facets — more than any other popular diamond shape including the round brilliant (57–58 facets).**

Standard radiant cut diamonds have 70 facets, designed to reflect light from every angle — making it one of the most brilliant of all rectangular diamonds.

### **The Facet Breakdown**

**Crown (top half) — approximately 25 facets:**

-   1 table facet (large, flat top)
-   8 bezel/kite facets
-   8 star facets
-   8 upper girdle facets

**Pavilion (bottom half) — approximately 45 facets:**

-   8 pavilion main facets
-   The additional pavilion facets (beyond round brilliant's 24) are what differentiate the radiant — extra rows create the intense "crushed ice" scintillation pattern distinctive to this shape

**The practical result:** More facets mean more light-refracting surfaces, which means more competing light paths returning to the eye simultaneously.

The radiant cut's 70 facets create a more complex, more continuous sparkle pattern than a round brilliant's 57–58 facets — though the geometric efficiency of the round brilliant's circular symmetry means round brilliants still typically outperform radiant in objective light return measurements.

The radiant's sparkle is more intense and "crushed" in character — hundreds of small competing reflections rather than the round's balanced macro-pattern.

## **What Are the Ideal Proportions for a Radiant Cut Diamond?**

**GIA does not issue a cut grade for radiant cut diamonds. Every proportion must be verified manually from the GIA certificate — making this the most important technical section in this guide.**

When Blue Nile lists a radiant as "Ideal Cut" or "Very Good Cut" — this is Blue Nile's retailer assessment, not a GIA laboratory grade. The same stone graded "Ideal" by one retailer might be "Very Good" by another. Your own proportion evaluation from the GIA certificate is the only reliable quality check.

### **Radiant Cut Ideal Proportion Table (2026)**

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>Proportion</th><th>Ideal Range</th><th>Acceptable Range</th><th>Avoid</th><th>Farzana’s Analytical Verdict</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>Table %</strong></td><td>58–68%</td><td>55–72%</td><td>Under 52% or over 75%</td><td><strong>10/10 — The Light Reflection Window.</strong> For a radiant cut, the table percentage directly controls the initial light intake. Keeping this metric strictly within the 58–68% ideal bracket prevents the diamond from looking flat. Going over 75% creates an unnaturally wide window that diminishes crucial crown sparkle, while dropping under 52% chokes off brilliance.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Depth %</strong></td><td>60–70%</td><td>58–74%</td><td>Under 56% (windowed) or over 76% (nail-head)</td><td><strong>10/10 — The Scintillation Engine.</strong> Depth controls how effectively a diamond bounces light back to your eye. If depth falls below 56%, light leaks straight through the bottom, creating a lifeless "window" effect. If it exceeds 76%, the center turns into a dark "nail-head" shadow, burying your expensive carat weight invisibly in the pavilion.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>L/W Ratio (Square)</strong></td><td>1.00–1.05</td><td>1.00–1.09</td><td>Over 1.12 (noticeably rectangular)</td><td><strong>9/10 — Pure Balanced Symmetry.</strong> To secure a crisp, visually square footprint, you want to stay as close to a true 1.00 ratio as possible. Once the metric creeps past 1.12, the stone gets trapped in a confusing visual gray zone—looking neither perfectly square nor purposefully rectangular. Keep it tight for sharp geometric style.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>L/W Ratio (Classic Rectangle)</strong></td><td>1.20–1.35</td><td>1.15–1.45</td><td>Under 1.10 (too square for elongated look)</td><td><strong>10/10 — The Elongated Standard.</strong> This is the universal sweet spot for premium rectangular presence. This specific ratio distributes the diamond's mass beautifully along the finger, creating a classic, elegant, hand-slimming silhouette. It maximizes face-up apparent size while completely safeguarding against center light leakage.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>L/W Ratio (Extended)</strong></td><td>1.35–1.50</td><td>1.30–1.55</td><td>Over 1.60 for most buyers</td><td><strong>9/10 — High-Impact Trendline.</strong> This bold, high-ratio profile delivers the striking vertical look of an emerald cut but charges it with fiery, brilliant-style faceting. However, stretching past 1.60 introduces severe optical risks, increasing the chance of a dark central bow-tie or structural glassiness. A strict video audit is mandatory here.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Girdle</strong></td><td>Thin–Slightly Thick</td><td>Very Thin–Thick</td><td>Extremely Thin (corner vulnerability)</td><td><strong>8/10 — The Structural Shield.</strong> The girdle acts as the foundational safety rim of the stone. An "Extremely Thin" rating leaves the radiant's cropped corners vulnerable to micro-chipping during everyday wear or setting pressure. Conversely, a "Very Thick" girdle hides useless, heavy weight along the rim that blows up the price without adding size.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Culet</strong></td><td>None / Pointed</td><td>Very Small</td><td>Medium or larger</td><td><strong>9/10 — The Focal Point Trap.</strong> The ideal culet should always be "None" or "Pointed," meaning the pavilion facets meet at a perfect, sharp point. If the culet is graded "Medium" or larger, that point is flattened off, creating a literal hole in the bottom of your diamond that registers visually as a dark, distracting dot right under the main table.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>Polish</strong></td><td>Excellent / Very Good</td><td>Good</td><td>Fair / Poor</td><td><strong>10/10 — The Surface Polish Premium.</strong> Polish directly dictates the mirror-like finish of the exterior facets. Settling for "Fair" or "Poor" means the stone will have microscopic surface scuffs and polishing lines left behind from the cutting wheel. This grit blocks light right at the doorstep, completely dulling the diamond's crispness.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Symmetry</strong></td><td>Excellent / Very Good</td><td>Good</td><td>Fair / Poor</td><td><strong>10/10 — Optical Alignment Security.</strong> For a radiant cut’s complex 70-facet design to fire in unison, facet alignment must be dead-on. Poor symmetry skews the facet angles, causing light to bounce out at random, unoptimized trajectories. Sticking to "Excellent" or "Very Good" ensures a balanced, symmetrical sparkle across the entire face.</td></tr></tbody></table>

### **The Depth Warning: The Radiant's Most Common Proportion Failure**

Depth over 74% in a radiant cut creates a combined "nail-head" and intensified crushed-ice effect — the stone appears darker in certain viewing angles and the brilliant sparkle becomes less even across the stone's surface. Deep radiant cuts also face up smaller for their stated carat weight — the extra weight is hidden in the pavilion rather than contributing to face-up surface area.

**The practical test:** A radiant with depth 62–68% and table 60–66% will face up larger and sparkle more evenly than a stone with depth 74%+ and table 55%. The GIA certificate's proportion section lists both values explicitly.

### **The L/W Ratio Decision**

<table class="dc-custom-table"><thead><tr><th>L/W Ratio</th><th>Visual</th><th>Best For</th><th>Farzana’s Analytical Verdict</th></tr></thead><tbody><tr><td><strong>1.00–1.05</strong></td><td>Square — the "square radiant"</td><td>Buyers who want a square shape more durable than princess</td><td><strong>8/10 — Symmetrical Shield.</strong> This profile serves as a highly functional, geometric anchor. It perfectly mimics the clean, architectural grid lines of a classic princess cut but uses cropped corners to eliminate fragile shearing points. While it offers zero vertical finger-lengthening magic, it concentrates light into a exceptionally dense, rapid-fire sparkle.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>1.10–1.20</strong></td><td>Slightly rectangular</td><td>Gentle elongation, works on all hand types</td><td><strong>7/10 — The Transitional Zone.</strong> Proceed with careful design intent here. This bracket sits in a subtle visual middle ground—it lacks the sharp, strict symmetry of a true square and doesn't quite commit to a striking rectangular stretch. It works beautifully as a soft, understated option for compact hand shapes, but can look slightly ambiguous if left unset.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>1.20–1.35</strong></td><td><strong>Classic elongated radiant</strong></td><td><strong>The most widely purchased configuration</strong></td><td><strong>10/10 — The Market Sweet Spot.</strong> The absolute golden standard of rectangular diamond geometry. This specific ratio strikes a flawless balance between vertical length and side-to-side width. It creates an incredibly elegant, slimming illusion on the hand while maintaining ideal internal facet angles that maximize the radiant's signature "crushed ice" brilliance.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>1.35–1.50</strong></td><td>Extended elongated — 2026 trend</td><td>Maximum finger-lengthening, contemporary</td><td><strong>9/10 — The Modern Elite Standard.</strong> A magnificent, high-impact silhouette that heavily dominates custom luxury design portfolios across mid-2026. It delivers the striking, commanding vertical spread of an emerald cut but charges it with explosive, brilliant-style fire. A rigorous 4K video audit is mandatory to verify that the extreme length hasn't created central light leakage.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>Over 1.50</strong></td><td>Dramatically elongated</td><td>Specialist preference, strong fashion statement</td><td><strong>6/10 — High-Variance Specialty Tier.</strong> An avant-garde, specialized configuration reserved for bold custom mountings (like east-west orientations). Stretching the crystal lattice this far pushes diamond optics to their absolute limits—dramatically increasing the risk of a dark central bow-tie shadow or glassy, lifeless zones. Only move forward under a certified gemologist's hands-on audit.</td></tr></tbody></table>

Much like the oval or marquise cuts, an elongated radiant cut has a magnificent slimming effect on the fingers, making the hand appear more graceful and slender. However, unlike the fragile pointed corners of a marquise or princess cut, the radiant cut features trimmed corners — making it incredibly durable.

