ener noreferrer">$4,830</a></strong></td><td><strong>9/10 — Premium Spread Extension.</strong> Pushing past the 1.00ct psychological barrier to 1.04ct under max-spec D-VVS1 Ideal conditions. The $4,830 markup scales very smoothly alongside its increased physical spread, keeping your capital optimization safe.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>1.21ct</strong></td><td>H-VVS1</td><td>Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28762246?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$4,850</a></strong></td><td><strong>10/10 — Exceptional Spread Arbitrage.</strong> This is an elite macro-weight victory. For less than $4.9k, you secure a massive 1.21ct spread. It completely dwarfs standard 1ct options face-up on the hand. If you are designing a classic yellow-gold solitaire ring, this stone stands as the ultimate size-for-value winner.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>1.01ct</strong></td><td>D-VVS1</td><td>Very Good</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28933192?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$4,880</a></strong></td><td><strong>4/10 — Inefficient Cut Deficit.</strong> Avoid. Pushing close to $4.9k for a diamond with an unoptimized "Very Good" cut grade is a major misallocation of capital, especially when flawless Ideal alternatives exist lower down the list. Pass.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>1.00ct</strong></td><td>D-VVS1</td><td>Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28657718?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$4,890</a></strong></td><td><strong>7/10 — Out-Indexed Precision.</strong> While this holds strong D-VVS1 Ideal specifications, it faces stiff competition from the top of our chart. Sourcing the identical matrix at a larger 1.02ct weight for only $4,650 leaves this specific unit out-indexed on value.</td></tr><tr><td><strong>1.01ct</strong></td><td>E-VVS1</td><td>Very Good</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29080915?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$4,980</a></strong></td><td><strong>3/10 — High Database Markup.</strong> A clear database trap. An E-color coupled with an inferior Very Good cut should never command a near-$5k premium when premium Ideal stones are trading $400 cheaper. Skip entirely.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>1.20ct</strong></td><td>H-VVS1</td><td>Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/23619585?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$4,990</a></strong></td><td rowspan="2"><strong>8/10 — High-Spread Twins.</strong> Landing right under the $5k psychological boundary, these twin 1.20ct stones offer immense hand presence. While they represent spectacular physical coverage, they are ultimately nudged out in sheer dollar efficiency by the superior 1.21ct stone sitting at $4,850.</td></tr><tr class="highlight-row"><td><strong>1.20ct</strong></td><td>H-VVS1</td><td>Ideal</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/27517576?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$4,990</a></strong></td></tr><tr><td><strong>1.01ct</strong></td><td>D-VVS1</td><td>Very Good</td><td><strong><a href="https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/29051377?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&amp;a_cid=55e51e63&amp;chan=blog-informational" target="_blank" rel="noopener noreferrer">$5,010</a></strong></td><td><strong>3/10 — Over-Priced Performance Deficit.</strong> Crossing past the $5k marker for an unoptimized "Very Good" cut profile is entirely unacceptable. This represents an unrewarded premium. Reject.</td></tr><tr cla