### **Critical Data Insights From the Live Price Audit**

**Insight 1 — The D vs. H paradox at VVS1:** The 1.02ct D-VVS1 Ideal at $4,650 and the 1.02ct H-VVS1 Ideal also at $4,650 — identical prices for D and H color at VVS1.

This is a genuine data anomaly in the current market. For buyers who understand that H color in a radiant cut in yellow gold is nearly indistinguishable from D, the H-VVS1 at **[$4,650](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/26558799?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)** is the better value — same price, same clarity, but redirected color savings are already built in.

**Insight 2 — H-VVS1 at 1.20ct+ for under $5,000:** The 1.20ct H-VVS1 Ideal at **[$4,990](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/23619585?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)** and 1.21ct H-VVS1 Ideal at **[$4,850](https://www.bluenile.com/diamond-details/28762246?a_aid=69d7c31a91b8d&a_cid=55e51e63&chan=blog-informational)** deliver over 20% more physical size than a 1ct stone for the same or lower price as many 1ct D-VVS1 stones.

For buyers who prioritize size, targeting H color at 1.20ct is dramatically more efficient than D color at 1.00ct.

**Insight 3 — Ideal vs. Very Good cut price variance:** At D-VVS1, three stones show: Ideal at $4,760, Very Good at $4,880, Very Good at $5,010. One Very Good costs $250 more than an Ideal of the same grade.

This confirms that within radiant cuts, "Ideal" and "Very Good" are retailer labels with no standardized relationship to actual light performance — proportion verification from the GIA certificate is more reliable than the cut label.

